#create two histogram 
g1<-accountT2 %>% ggplot()+
  geom_histogram(aes(x=loan_amount,fill=loan_status),bins=20)+
  labs(title='Loan amount with loan_status')

g2<-accountT2 %>% ggplot()+
  geom_histogram(aes(x=loan_amount,fill=loan_default),bins=20)+
  labs(title='Loan amount with loan_default')
# arrange these two plot in one line
grid.arrange(g1, g2, nrow = 1)

The plot above shows the number of loan not-defaulted account is much more than the number of loan defaulted account. And the number of expired loan account is lower than current loan account. Both current and expired loan account which is not in default have amount value concdntrating in 0 to 2e+05.

accountT2 %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(aes(x=loan_payment,fill=loan_default),bins=30)+
  facet_wrap(~loan_status) +
  theme_dark() +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Loan_payment with loan_status and loan_default") +
  xlab("Loan_payment") +
  ylab("Count")

The plot above shows that payment value of current account which is not in default concentrate in 1250 to 5000.

accountT2 %>% 
  ggplot()+
  geom_point(aes(x=loan_term,y=loan_amount),color = 'blue',size = 2,alpha = 1/5)+
  facet_wrap(~loan_status)+
  labs(title='Loan amount with loan term in current and expried account')+
  xlab('Loan term')+
  ylab('Loan Amount')

The plot above shows that the loan amount value range increase with the loan term increases. But for the expired account, there are fewer long term loan.
